<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="273" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,720,871,933]" box="[151,311,907,933]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<figureCitation box="[151,311,907,933]" captionStart="FIGURES 228–247" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[157,1425,191,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-16@22.[151,1436,181,1836]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 228–247. Male genitalia. 228–233―Anaceratagallia (Anaceratagallia) aciculata, 234–236―A. (A.) kungradica, 237–238―A. (A.) aciculata sensu Khatri et al., 2010, 239–240―A. (A.) seriphidii, holotype, 241–245―A. (A.) acuteangulata, 246–247―A. (Oedicora) kerzhneri. 228, 230, 232, 234, 237, 239, 241–242, 246―penis, lateral view, 229, 231, 233, 235–236, 240, 243–245―male anal collar appendage, 238―end of pygofer lobe and male anal collar appendage, 247―end of pygofer lobe. 234–236―after Dubovsky (1967), 237–238―after Khatri et al. (2010)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4398510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4398510/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Figs. 246–247</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,979,1294]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,979,1005]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Description.</emphasis>
In external appearance and coloration similar to species of nominotypical subgenus. Penis stem gradually tapering towards apex, not flattened laterally, with two lateral lamellar expansions (
<figureCitation box="[1136,1234,1015,1042]" captionStart="FIGURES 228–247" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[157,1425,191,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-16@22.[151,1436,181,1836]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 228–247. Male genitalia. 228–233―Anaceratagallia (Anaceratagallia) aciculata, 234–236―A. (A.) kungradica, 237–238―A. (A.) aciculata sensu Khatri et al., 2010, 239–240―A. (A.) seriphidii, holotype, 241–245―A. (A.) acuteangulata, 246–247―A. (Oedicora) kerzhneri. 228, 230, 232, 234, 237, 239, 241–242, 246―penis, lateral view, 229, 231, 233, 235–236, 240, 243–245―male anal collar appendage, 238―end of pygofer lobe and male anal collar appendage, 247―end of pygofer lobe. 234–236―after Dubovsky (1967), 237–238―after Khatri et al. (2010)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4398510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4398510/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Fig. 246</figureCitation>
). Male anal collar without appendages; the latter fused with upper margin of pygofer and looks like additional tooth on pygofer lobe (
<figureCitation box="[160,258,1087,1113]" captionStart="FIGURES 228–247" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[157,1425,191,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-16@22.[151,1436,181,1836]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 228–247. Male genitalia. 228–233―Anaceratagallia (Anaceratagallia) aciculata, 234–236―A. (A.) kungradica, 237–238―A. (A.) aciculata sensu Khatri et al., 2010, 239–240―A. (A.) seriphidii, holotype, 241–245―A. (A.) acuteangulata, 246–247―A. (Oedicora) kerzhneri. 228, 230, 232, 234, 237, 239, 241–242, 246―penis, lateral view, 229, 231, 233, 235–236, 240, 243–245―male anal collar appendage, 238―end of pygofer lobe and male anal collar appendage, 247―end of pygofer lobe. 234–236―after Dubovsky (1967), 237–238―after Khatri et al. (2010)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4398510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4398510/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Fig. 247</figureCitation>
). Pygofer lobe gradually tapering towards apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="273" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,979,1294]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1123,1149]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Biology.</emphasis>
In Transbaikalia we collected 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Emelyanov" baseAuthorityYear="1987" box="[639,843,1123,1150]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Anaceratagallia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kerzhneri" subGenus="Oe.">
<emphasis box="[639,664,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">A.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[680,720,1124,1150]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Oe.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[737,843,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">kerzhneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at the end of June on steppe slopes on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Spiraea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aquilegifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Spiraea aquilegifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[259,371,1159,1185]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Emelyanov, A. F." box="[542,754,1159,1185]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" pagination="22 - 30" refId="ref13251" refString="Emelyanov, A. F. (1987) New species of leafhoppers (Homoptera, Cicadina) from the Far East and Eastern Siberia. Taxonomy of insects of Siberia and the Far East of the USSR, Vladivostok, 1987, 22 - 30. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1987">Emelyanov (1987)</bibRefCitation>
, males of this species are very rare.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,979,1294]" box="[199,495,1195,1221]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,370,1195,1221]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Calling signal.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="273" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,979,1294]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1231,1257]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Distribution.</emphasis>
Eastern Transbaikalia (Chita Oblast, the Talacha River Valley near the confluence with the Ingoda River, 
<quantity box="[288,359,1267,1293]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" unit="km" value="10.0">10 km</quantity>
West of Urul’ga Village; new record), Amur Oblast, 
<collectingCountry box="[953,1062,1267,1293]" name="Mongolia" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
(only females).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
